class Solution {
public:
    bool isSubsequence(string s, string t) {
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while (i < s.size() && j < t.size()) {
            if (s[i] == t[j]) i++;
            j++;
        }
        return i == s.size();
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates through both strings once, using two pointers. It checks for matching characters and advances the pointer for string s only when a match is found. If all characters in s are matched in order, it returns true; otherwise, it returns false. For the follow-up scenario, pre-processing t into a data structure like a hash map or trie can improve efficiency for multiple incoming strings s.

